            <p>Conductor Linus Lerner is praised for his musical influence and charisma both symphonic and choral podium, as in the opera pit. Linus conducted several groups in the United States, Brazil, Bulgaria, China, Czech Republic, Mexico, Spain and Turkey.</p>
            <p>Currently holds the role of artistic director and conductor of the Southern Arizona Symphony Orchestra (SASO) in Tucson, AZ, the Orchestra Sinfonica Rio Grande do Norte - OSRN (artistic director and guest conductor) and the Opera of Oaxaca in Mexico Festival.</p>
            <p>With the SASO, performs regular season of 14 annual concerts, and other events. With the same also held two tournees several cities and Chinese composers recording a CD of the city of Tucson.</p> 
            <p>As a manager and artistic director of OSRN, has performed many concerts and events in Natal.</p>
            <p>To take the invitation of artistic director of OSRN, conductor Linus Lerner recently left his post as conductor and artistic director of choirs BCPA with whom held numerous performances in the most prestigious theaters in Houston, plus CD's recordings and performances with Houston Pops Orchestra and the Texas Medical Center Orchestra. With the latter, has just made his debut at Carnegie Hall in May 2013.</p>
            <p>Linus Lerner has also worked as a conductor associated to the Opera of the Ozarks, the Youth Orchestra of Tallahassee and Philarmonica Orchestra of the University of Arizona.</p>
            <p>As a guest conductor, he has reacted the Orchestre National de Vales in Spain; the Symphony Orchestra of Porto Alegre; the International Opera Workshop of Bulgaria and the Czech Republic; the Soloists Ensemble del Instituto Nacional de Bellas Mexico Arts; Opera Company of Brooklyn, New York; Opera at the University of Colorado at Boulder; Opera in the Heights in Houston, the Symphony Orchestra of Hunan in China, the Orchestra Tsintao in China, the Orchestra of Fuzhou in China, the Orchestra Spring in Mexico, the Wick Chamber Orchestra and Singers in Arizona and was Opera assistant conductor of the Arizona. In 2011 he was artistic director of the Beijing Opera Festival culminating in the production of "Magic Flute" with the National Radio and Television Orchestra and Chinese singers of Opera Nacinal Chinese. In 2012 we held the second edition of the festival in Beijing beyond the first edition as artistic director of the Festival of Oaxaca in Mexico.</p>
            <p>Linus Lerner completed her Ph.D. in orchestral conducting by University of Arizona (UA) where he was assistant conductor of opera and the symphony orchestra of the same, conducting several performances in Tucson and in tournee by Mexico in 2002.</p>
            <p>Linux also has two master's degrees in music: one in orchestral conducting from Florida State University where he was assistant conductor of orchestras, performing in numerous performances including Premiere American Opera Procedura Penale Luciano Chally; the second in Vocal Performance (opera) at the Conservatory of Music at the University of Cincinnati. It also has a bachelor's degree in choral conducting from the Federal University of Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil.</p>
            <p>In addition to his experience as an orchestral conductor and opera, Dr. Linus Lerner has extensive experience as a conductor of choirs. Dr. Linus Lerner worked with more than 50 groups of various sizes and combinations of voices, and participated in numerous tournees, festivals and competitions. Linus has given courses and provided enhancement to several professional choirs, schools, communities and churches in Brazil and in Mexico and the United States.</p>
            <p>As a singer, Linus has participated in several operas and concerts in the United States, Europe, Brazil and Mexico and has received awards in competitions such as the Competition Neyde Thomas, Competition for Soloists of the OSPA and Miami University Concerto Competition.</p>
            <p>Linus Lerner also acts as a singing teacher and 'voice coach' and travels regularly to teach conducting singers and students in the US, Mexico, Brazil and China.</p>
